node.text:
Child Rescue Coalition is proud to have collaborated with the UK Border Force to produce this awareness raising video from the perspective of a parent. This is based on a real case and is the second in a series of three.

Parents everywhere are struggling to keep up with technology. Knowing what makes an online game or app dangerous allows parents to identify the dangers and to empower their children to protect themselves in the online environment.

This parent's child became the victim of an online predator, please make sure your family is not the next one to suffer from this horrific abuse.

This resource is available in 10 native languages, is presented by Child Rescue Coalition and made possible through the support of the UK Home Office. We are grateful for your support in spreading this message to protect children across the globe.

node.text:
We are proud to release this awareness video from the perspective of law enforcement officers, it is the first in a series of three. Officers do an incredibly difficult job helping to protect children from dangerous pedophiles. An offender may have known their victim for many years, or could be causing the abuse from thousands of miles away.

No one organization can tackle this problem, but by sharing what they've learned and working together - we can ALL make a difference. It takes a network to defeat a network, and we all need to join the fight to prevent this abuse from happening.

This resource is available in 10 native languages, and is presented by Child Rescue Coalition, and made possible through the support of the UK Home Office. We are grateful for your support in spreading this message to protect kids across the globe.

node.text:
When Jeremy turned 24, his life began to change. He started having severe bouts of sadness. These episodes started lasting hours, and they came coupled with memories of when he was a young 8-year-old boy and was abused. He had decided to fight the memories, but that wasn't working only making things worse.

He knew he needed to do something about it, so he searched for an outlet to express what had happened to him. He started using open mics as a way of sharing his story to encourage others but the audience there was not right for his platform and he would at times get harassed.

He thought he couldn’t take one more night, but knew the best option was to keep going. He started getting creative with how he told his story and it was catching people’s attention. And with this, he knew he was on to something. Jeremy has now been speaking out in public for two years.

He, like us, believes that we must bring more attention to this subject, which is essential if we stand any chance of breaking the stigma and the silence. Let's encourage others to #jointhefigt and speak out because that's the first step into making a change.

Written by: @jeremyindika 
Animation by: @kingbeeanimation 
Sound Design: @leemas9

.

.
.
.
.

node.text:
Law enforcement officers used Child Rescue Coalition technology to gather evidence that indicated the suspect, Min Hao Wu, 35, had a very dangerous interest in young children, including the violent sexual abuse of very young children.

The suspect claimed he didn’t have a sexual interest in very young children but that he was a “hebephile”. This is the technical term for someone who has a sexual interest in young teenage children.

Evidence collected thanks to CRC technology showed a different story. It showed that he was a pedophile, as he did have an extremely dangerous interest in young children.

He now faces felony charges for his crimes against children.

Lucy Hale is probably best known for her role on @prettylittleliars , but what you may not know is that she is also an avid supporter of the work we do here at Child Rescue Coalition.

"We have to protect them [children]. We have to do everything we can. And where I can step in is talking about it....to get ears and eyes on this issue."

Hear more about why Lucy supports Child Rescue Coalition on IGTV where she sits down for a candid discussion with CRC Founder and CEO @carlyyoostcrc.

node.text:
This statistic demonstrates the gravity of each and every arrest. When a predator is stopped, their current victim is not the only one saved -- there are potentially DOZENS more lives spared from their abuse.

85% of people who consume child sexual abuse material are also hands-on abusers of children, meaning each predator caught protects up to 40 children from online sexual exploitation and/or hands-on sexual abuse.

Will you join us in this fight? Check the link in bio to learn how you can get involved or to make a donation.

It involves building a mutual relationship built on trust, intimacy, and vulnerability. -Lexie, SURVIVOR CHiLDRE CHLD COALI TION CHiLD'.

node.text:
The importance of establishing trust with your kids cannot be understated. Keeping kids safe from online predators is not about being a helicopter parent or never trusting your child. It's about building a foundation of trust and communication to equip children with the resources and relationships they need to feel supported and empowered.

It's never too early to start talking to kids about body and internet safety in age-appropriate ways. For parenting and safety tips, or to read Lexie's story, head to our blog at the link in bio.

Do you know what 🍝 means? How about 🔨?

It's World Emoji Day and we've partnered with our friends at @barktechnologies to decode some common emoji slang. These emojis may look innocent enough, but they're often used to represent graphic and sexual concepts.

Be on the lookout for these emojis and have honest conversations with your kids about what's appropriate and how to stay safe.

⚠️TRIGGER WARNING⚠️ 

Many of us use video platforms for business meetings or to catch up with friends and family. But did you know that these common tools are also used, on a daily basis, for “Live Streaming Abuse” or “Online Child Sexual Exploitation”?

The victim of live-streamed abuse can be raped 10, 20, or even more times in a single day.  Before the rape starts the child is forced to smile and even wave at the unknown buyer who is often many thousands of miles away.

Then the unthinkable happens. The buyer proceeds to direct the rape of the child, describing what he (almost always a “he”) wants the rapist to do.

Our new technology is focused on helping investigators process of tens of thousands of lines of data from multiple sources and in multiple formats. This allows them to “see” the suspects and to do their job – investigate the criminals and rescue the children – not spend their valuable time trying to make sense of numerous spreadsheets and images.

Read more on our blog at the link in bio.

Child Rescue Coalition is proud to have collaborated with the UK Border Force to produce this awareness raising video from the perspective of a parent. This is based on a real case and is the second in a series of three.

Parents everywhere are struggling to keep up with technology. Knowing what makes an online game or app dangerous allows parents to identify the dangers and to empower their children to protect themselves in the online environment.

This parent's child became the victim of an online predator, please make sure your family is not the next one to suffer from this horrific abuse.

This resource is available in 10 native languages, is presented by Child Rescue Coalition and made possible through the support of the UK Home Office. We are grateful for your support in spreading this message to protect children across the globe.

It’s important for all parents to understand how a predator works in order to thoroughly protect their children. Watch for these signs. Get in the habit of checking your kids' devices. Have frequent and honest conversations about online safety with your kids so that they are educated and empowered to protect themselves.

If we don't teach our own children, they will learn from someone else -- and that someone could be a sex predator.

Read more on our blog at the link in bio.
